  "text": "anchor Image rendering courtesy Negativ New renderings for the forthcoming Las Vegas A’s MLB stadium were released earlier by BIG and HNTB ahead of the planned start of construction work later this year. The approximately $1.5 billion project was first announced in March of 2024 as a retractable roof design with 33,000 seats and the world’s largest cable-net glass wall aperture in left field. Image rendering courtesy NegativTypical to a number of Bjarke Ingels’ other large-scale designs, the form of the roof itself is derived from layered shells contrived in the shape of baseball pennants. The left field feature, which is akin to (but bigger than) the \"living room\" effect accomplished in Miami’s Loan Depot Park, frames views of Las Vegas’ commercial district further on. It will also have the MLB’s largest video screen. Ingels has said the design is \"like a spherical armadillo.\" Image rendering courtesy NegativNew images of its interior give a clearer picture of what the fan experience will be like during games. The firms say their collaboration will establish a \"sense of openness, intuitive navigation, and a rich layering of social experiences.\" Image rendering courtesy NegativImage rendering courtesy NegativImage rendering courtesy NegativThis includes a unique outfield entry sequence framed by “bouncing\" arches, a home plate bar and tiered social lounges, and stacked bullpens that bring fans closer to the action. Image rendering courtesy NegativThroughout the park, in-seat air conditioning will be another comfort-serving component. HNTB’s Design Director of Interiors, Emily Louchart, says it’s about \"creating moments that connect fans to the action, the team, and each other.\" Image rendering courtesy NegativThe stadium is on track to be ready in time for Opening Day of the 2028 baseball season. The A's will be playing their home games in the upgraded Sutter Health Park, an HNTB design from 2000, in Sacramento until then.",
